WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:04.970
&gt;&gt; Speaker One: From the Library
of Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:18.640 --> 00:00:20.170
&gt;&gt; Ann Brener: Good afternoon.

00:00:20.170 --> 00:00:24.390
On behalf of Mary-Jane
Deeb, Chief of the African

00:00:24.390 --> 00:00:27.350
and Middle Eastern Division,
I would like to welcome you

00:00:27.350 --> 00:00:29.360
to the Library of Congress.

00:00:29.360 --> 00:00:31.660
My name is Ann Brener
and I'm a specialist

00:00:31.660 --> 00:00:35.160
in the Hebraic Section, here.

00:00:35.160 --> 00:00:39.570
In the spring of 2017 the
Library of Congress learned

00:00:39.570 --> 00:00:42.540
of an extraordinary
treasure on the market,

00:00:42.540 --> 00:00:44.520
a most unique ancient fragment

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:47.510
from the biblical
book of Exodus.

00:00:47.510 --> 00:00:49.700
Just how unique you'll
soon be hearing

00:00:49.700 --> 00:00:52.190
from our wonderful speaker.

00:00:52.190 --> 00:00:54.260
Now, the story of Exodus is one

00:00:54.260 --> 00:00:57.580
of the foundational
texts of Western culture.

00:00:57.580 --> 00:01:00.500
It is woven into the American
narrative about freedom

00:01:00.500 --> 00:01:04.310
and it resonates powerfully
in American history.

00:01:04.310 --> 00:01:06.160
What could be more
fitting, therefore,

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:08.820
than to bring this ancient
treasure to the Library

00:01:08.820 --> 00:01:12.070
of Congress, the national
library of the nation founded

00:01:12.070 --> 00:01:14.880
on the principle of freedom?

00:01:14.880 --> 00:01:17.900
Now, the ancient
treasure is actually here.

00:01:17.900 --> 00:01:20.000
And for this, we have to
thank the people at the helm

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:22.720
of the library, the ones who
make the actual decisions

00:01:22.720 --> 00:01:25.530
on what to apply and what not.

00:01:25.530 --> 00:01:28.620
It takes more, I think, than
the power of the purse to make

00:01:28.620 --> 00:01:31.100
to make that kind of decision.

00:01:31.100 --> 00:01:34.280
To quote from the Hebrew poem
written by a grateful poet

00:01:34.280 --> 00:01:38.010
to this patron over thousand
years ago in medieval Spain,

00:01:38.010 --> 00:01:40.090
''It also takes heart
and mind and eye.''

00:01:40.090 --> 00:01:43.590
And those words remain
true, today.

00:01:43.590 --> 00:01:46.840
Please, join me, therefore,
in making Mary-Jane Deeb,

00:01:46.840 --> 00:01:49.820
the Chief of the African
and Middle Eastern Division,

00:01:49.820 --> 00:01:51.890
Beacher Wiggins,
Director of Acquisitions

00:01:51.890 --> 00:01:53.190
and Bibliographic Access.

00:01:53.190 --> 00:01:57.530
And most of all, I
think, Helena Zinkham,

00:01:57.530 --> 00:01:59.480
Director of Collections
and Services.

00:01:59.480 --> 00:02:03.960
Without them we wouldn't be
celebrating here to today.

00:02:03.960 --> 00:02:07.550
Today's speaker also played
an important role behind

00:02:07.550 --> 00:02:09.010
the scenes.

00:02:09.010 --> 00:02:10.710
It was to him I turned
when I first learned

00:02:10.710 --> 00:02:14.110
of this ancient scroll sheet
and it was his expertise

00:02:14.110 --> 00:02:17.640
that guided me during
the crucial first stage.

00:02:17.640 --> 00:02:20.280
For this reason, I am
delighted, doubly delighted,

00:02:20.280 --> 00:02:22.280
that the day has finally come

00:02:22.280 --> 00:02:25.550
when we can welcome Professor
Rendsburg into our meeting room

00:02:25.550 --> 00:02:29.250
and hear more about
our new treasure.

00:02:29.250 --> 00:02:34.200
In addition to being my
own special consultant Gary

00:02:34.200 --> 00:02:36.850
Rosenburg, Rendsburg is
a distinguished professor

00:02:36.850 --> 00:02:40.390
of Jewish history at
Rutgers University,

00:02:40.390 --> 00:02:41.690
where he holds the Blanche

00:02:41.690 --> 00:02:44.350
and Irving Laurie Chair
in Jewish History.

00:02:44.350 --> 00:02:48.650
He is author of seven books of
Biblical literature and language

00:02:48.650 --> 00:02:51.810
and about 170 articles.

00:02:51.810 --> 00:02:54.370
That's one seven zero.

00:02:54.370 --> 00:02:56.540
Perhaps, his best-known
book is the Bible

00:02:56.540 --> 00:02:58.310
and Ancient Near
East co-authored

00:02:58.310 --> 00:03:01.480
with the late Sirus Gordon.

00:03:01.480 --> 00:03:05.660
He has also produced two DVDs
for The Great Courses program,

00:03:05.660 --> 00:03:09.860
one on the book of Genesis and
one on the Dead Sea Scrolls.

00:03:09.860 --> 00:03:14.240
He is, also, my former professor
from graduate school in Cornell

00:03:14.240 --> 00:03:16.940
and I'm sure is grading
me today.

00:03:16.940 --> 00:03:20.510
So, please join me in welcoming
Professor Gary Rendsburg.

00:03:20.510 --> 00:03:26.720
[ Applause ]

00:03:26.720 --> 00:03:28.020
&gt;&gt; Gary Rendsburg: Thank
you, very much, Ann,

00:03:28.020 --> 00:03:32.170
for those very kind words and
it's such a pleasure to be here.

00:03:32.170 --> 00:03:34.300
And as you said, you
use the word celebrate.

00:03:34.300 --> 00:03:40.440
It's truly a time of celebration
to reflect on the arrival

00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:46.580
of the remarkable 1,000-year-old
Torah scroll sheet now here

00:03:46.580 --> 00:03:48.310
at the Library of Congress.

00:03:48.310 --> 00:03:52.230
The oldest Torah scroll
sheet in the world,

00:03:52.230 --> 00:03:54.950
complete Torah scroll
sheet in the world,

00:03:54.950 --> 00:03:57.250
legible to the naked eye.

00:03:57.250 --> 00:04:00.920
And that's how we can define
this treasure that is now part

00:04:00.920 --> 00:04:03.730
of the Library of Congress.

00:04:03.730 --> 00:04:08.170
So, let's discuss
how it got here,

00:04:08.170 --> 00:04:10.920
why it's so important,
why it's so unique.

00:04:10.920 --> 00:04:16.620
And just join me for this
amazing beautiful ride.

00:04:16.620 --> 00:04:23.890
So, as Ann said, in
last spring in May 2017,

00:04:23.890 --> 00:04:26.580
she sends me an email
and she says,

00:04:26.580 --> 00:04:29.320
''Would you please take
a look at this catalog?''

00:04:29.320 --> 00:04:31.730
And these are some
snippets from this catalog,

00:04:31.730 --> 00:04:34.990
''The 19th Century Rare
Book and Photograph Shop''.

00:04:34.990 --> 00:04:38.470
And they have offices in
both Brooklyn, New York

00:04:38.470 --> 00:04:42.950
and Stevenson just outside
of Baltimore, Maryland.

00:04:42.950 --> 00:04:47.670
''And please, go look at
this item, in particular,

00:04:47.670 --> 00:04:53.710
on page 129 of the
catalog.'' Which I do.

00:04:53.710 --> 00:04:56.130
And I read it and it
says, as you can see here,

00:04:56.130 --> 00:04:58.060
that is all we have to go on.

00:04:58.060 --> 00:05:01.320
Exodus 1010 through 1615.

00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:04.940
Complete biblical
scroll sheet in Hebrew.

00:05:04.940 --> 00:05:09.910
A Torah scroll panel, Middle
East, tenth or 11th century.

00:05:09.910 --> 00:05:13.030
And then, a more
detailed description.

00:05:13.030 --> 00:05:16.850
So, when I see this, and I'll
just close, give you a close-up

00:05:16.850 --> 00:05:21.450
on the most important part
of the catalog description.

00:05:21.450 --> 00:05:23.980
I know, immediately, what it is.

00:05:23.980 --> 00:05:26.740
And that's because those
of us who work in the field

00:05:26.740 --> 00:05:29.090
of Hebrew manuscripts keep
track of these things.

00:05:29.090 --> 00:05:32.040
We certainly know where they
are in public collections,

00:05:32.040 --> 00:05:35.090
in libraries, and
museums around the world.

00:05:35.090 --> 00:05:36.950
And even, those which
are in private hands,

00:05:36.950 --> 00:05:39.450
we learn about from
time to time.

00:05:39.450 --> 00:05:44.100
This one was sold at
Christie's in London in 2001,

00:05:44.100 --> 00:05:45.890
and therefore, I knew about it.

00:05:45.890 --> 00:05:50.240
But, of course, one never
knows who the seller is

00:05:50.240 --> 00:05:52.890
or who the buyer is
in such private sales

00:05:52.890 --> 00:05:55.810
through auction houses like
Christie's or Sotheby's

00:05:55.810 --> 00:05:58.800
and other such institutions
in the world.

00:05:58.800 --> 00:06:01.000
Now, that I know
exactly what it was.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:02.910
I had a pretty good
hint, but of course,

00:06:02.910 --> 00:06:06.620
I didn't remember Exodus
1010 through Exodus 1615.

00:06:06.620 --> 00:06:08.290
I said that must be it, but I

00:06:08.290 --> 00:06:10.410
of course went back
and double checked.

00:06:10.410 --> 00:06:11.910
And indeed, it was.

00:06:11.910 --> 00:06:14.500
Why did I know about it?

00:06:14.500 --> 00:06:17.780
Because, kudos to Jordan
Penkower, my colleague

00:06:17.780 --> 00:06:20.480
at Bar Ilan University
in Israel.

00:06:20.480 --> 00:06:23.340
Who, in the year 2002 was able

00:06:23.340 --> 00:06:26.370
to publish a very
long detailed article

00:06:26.370 --> 00:06:29.260
about the Torah scroll
sheet that is now here

00:06:29.260 --> 00:06:30.560
at the Library of Congress.

00:06:30.560 --> 00:06:36.010
Which, is to say when it was
for auction in London in 2001,

00:06:36.010 --> 00:06:39.060
he as an expert in
medieval Hebrew manuscripts

00:06:39.060 --> 00:06:42.690
and Torah scrolls, in
particular, was invited to come

00:06:42.690 --> 00:06:44.020
to London to study it.

00:06:44.020 --> 00:06:45.770
So, that it would, at
least, be available

00:06:45.770 --> 00:06:47.570
for the scholarly world.

00:06:47.570 --> 00:06:49.430
Even though, it would,
presumably, be purchased

00:06:49.430 --> 00:06:52.100
by somebody in private
hands as it was.

00:06:52.100 --> 00:06:54.460
And here is his description
of it, exactly,

00:06:54.460 --> 00:06:57.550
with the same verse, of
course, that are in the catalog

00:06:57.550 --> 00:06:59.150
that we just looked at.

00:06:59.150 --> 00:07:01.010
And the same dimensions
and so on.

00:07:01.010 --> 00:07:04.430
So, I confirmed by looking
at Jordan Penkower's article

00:07:04.430 --> 00:07:08.480
from 16, at that
time, 15 years ago,

00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:10.370
that this was, indeed,
the sheet.

00:07:10.370 --> 00:07:12.030
And I emailed Ann back.

00:07:12.030 --> 00:07:14.890
I think her email to me was
something like, ''Is this real?

00:07:14.890 --> 00:07:16.190
Is this possible?

00:07:16.190 --> 00:07:19.300
It's too good to be true.''
Is was something like that.

00:07:19.300 --> 00:07:20.890
And I wrote her and I said.

00:07:20.890 --> 00:07:22.550
''This is real.

00:07:22.550 --> 00:07:25.430
Buy it if you can.'' Right.

00:07:25.430 --> 00:07:27.460
Obviously, okay.

00:07:27.460 --> 00:07:30.430
And Ann already described
the processes, of course,

00:07:30.430 --> 00:07:33.940
at any institution, as
we are all aware of,

00:07:33.940 --> 00:07:36.520
of how such a thing
needs to be obtained.

00:07:36.520 --> 00:07:39.180
Pardon? Right.

00:07:39.180 --> 00:07:44.940
So, it was purchased by the
library, as we've just heard.

00:07:44.940 --> 00:07:48.130
Now, Penkower published, when
he published his very long,

00:07:48.130 --> 00:07:53.350
detailed article, two very
not so good photos from,

00:07:53.350 --> 00:07:55.900
I don't know if he took
them with his own camera.

00:07:55.900 --> 00:08:00.460
Black and white photos
from 2001, 2002.

00:08:00.460 --> 00:08:04.040
And these are the two photos
he took, and a portion

00:08:04.040 --> 00:08:08.190
of column three and a
portion of column five,

00:08:08.190 --> 00:08:09.710
just to give us a sense.

00:08:09.710 --> 00:08:11.790
Now, column five is
the important one

00:08:11.790 --> 00:08:14.680
because as you see there,
while the entire text,

00:08:14.680 --> 00:08:17.050
and I'll show it to you,
again, in a few moments,

00:08:17.050 --> 00:08:20.710
is written out in prose.

00:08:20.710 --> 00:08:24.780
The portion of Exodus 15
known as the Song of the Sea,

00:08:24.780 --> 00:08:28.480
Shirat Ha Yam in Hebrew,
is written out in poetry.

00:08:28.480 --> 00:08:31.340
And it's a very well-known
poetic structure

00:08:31.340 --> 00:08:34.820
that biblical text
of Torah scrolls

00:08:34.820 --> 00:08:40.030
of this particular song
use the poetic style.

00:08:40.030 --> 00:08:42.610
So, there you see some of
the handwriting up close

00:08:42.610 --> 00:08:47.270
and personal in images which
are taken some years ago.

00:08:47.270 --> 00:08:52.110
I also went online and there
is an auction record of it

00:08:52.110 --> 00:08:56.660
from this invaluable.com,
which you know,

00:08:56.660 --> 00:08:59.070
tracks and keeps records
of all these things.

00:08:59.070 --> 00:09:01.490
And again, a very poor
image on the left,

00:09:01.490 --> 00:09:05.570
upper left there you can see
of the of scroll fragment.

00:09:05.570 --> 00:09:08.910
And on the right, a
bilingual inscription.

00:09:08.910 --> 00:09:10.930
I'll show you a better
copy in a moment.

00:09:10.930 --> 00:09:14.850
In Russian and in Hebrew,
which gives us a clue as to

00:09:14.850 --> 00:09:18.510
where it was, at least
in the year 1863.

00:09:18.510 --> 00:09:21.690
And that inscription is
on the back of the scroll.

00:09:21.690 --> 00:09:27.260
We learned from this
that it was presented

00:09:27.260 --> 00:09:29.900
by a man named Shelomo Beim.

00:09:29.900 --> 00:09:35.430
He was the Karaite Hazzan in
the Crimea in the 19th century.

00:09:35.430 --> 00:09:38.790
We know about him from
other sources, as well.

00:09:38.790 --> 00:09:41.570
So, the Karaites
are a group of Jews

00:09:41.570 --> 00:09:45.110
who do not follow the
rabbinic approach.

00:09:45.110 --> 00:09:47.590
The rabbinical movement
which arose in the second

00:09:47.590 --> 00:09:51.070
and third century CE has
been the dominant one

00:09:51.070 --> 00:09:52.490
down to the present day.

00:09:52.490 --> 00:09:56.090
And all modern streams of
Judaism, orthodox, conservative,

00:09:56.090 --> 00:09:58.030
reform, Reconstructionist,

00:09:58.030 --> 00:10:01.400
and now in the 21st century
renewal, and everything else.

00:10:01.400 --> 00:10:03.640
Are all based on the
rabbinic system as laid

00:10:03.640 --> 00:10:07.580
out by the classical rabbis in
the Mishnah and the Talmidim.

00:10:07.580 --> 00:10:10.060
The Karaites have a totally
different approach to Judaism

00:10:10.060 --> 00:10:13.740
which does not use the rabbinic
system and they are a community

00:10:13.740 --> 00:10:16.970
of about 50,000 down
to the present day.

00:10:16.970 --> 00:10:18.830
Mainly in Israel,
but once upon a time,

00:10:18.830 --> 00:10:21.030
spread out throughout
the near East.

00:10:21.030 --> 00:10:25.930
Large communities in Egypt and
in parts of Russia, as well,

00:10:25.930 --> 00:10:28.600
both in Lithuania and next door.

00:10:28.600 --> 00:10:31.430
So, this is Shelomo
Beim, a Karaite Hazzan,

00:10:31.430 --> 00:10:32.850
leader of the community.

00:10:32.850 --> 00:10:35.970
I think Hazzan in the Karaite
system means less the canter

00:10:35.970 --> 00:10:37.270
in the synagogue, but rather,

00:10:37.270 --> 00:10:39.380
the one who oversees
the community.

00:10:39.380 --> 00:10:42.910
And he gave it as a gift to
the Grand Duke Constantine,

00:10:42.910 --> 00:10:47.340
the brother of Czar
Alexander II in the year 1863.

00:10:47.340 --> 00:10:50.490
That's what the Russian and
Hebrew inscription says.

00:10:50.490 --> 00:10:52.180
And again, I'll show you
a better image of it.

00:10:52.180 --> 00:10:54.550
We now have a very
good image of it.

00:10:54.550 --> 00:10:57.990
So, it tells us, of course,
that this was there in 1863.

00:10:57.990 --> 00:10:59.290
How did it get there?

00:10:59.290 --> 00:11:02.800
According to Penkower and
everybody else who's seen it,

00:11:02.800 --> 00:11:05.330
it is written in
the Middle East.

00:11:05.330 --> 00:11:09.490
That is to say, we can tell
handwritings and we divide them

00:11:09.490 --> 00:11:11.490
up into various geographical
zones.

00:11:11.490 --> 00:11:13.750
Spain, which we call
the Sephardic one.

00:11:13.750 --> 00:11:16.460
Europe which we call northern
Europe, the Ashkenazi one.

00:11:16.460 --> 00:11:17.870
The Yemenite one.

00:11:17.870 --> 00:11:20.310
And this would be the
Middle Eastern hand.

00:11:20.310 --> 00:11:23.170
And it's pretty clear that
it came from the Middle East.

00:11:23.170 --> 00:11:25.710
And based on other
elements, we know that it's

00:11:25.710 --> 00:11:28.270
about 1,000 years old.

00:11:28.270 --> 00:11:33.100
So, when I was here in the
October 2017, it was still,

00:11:33.100 --> 00:11:35.520
it had recently arrived
and it was still

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:39.900
in its original glass
case and frame.

00:11:39.900 --> 00:11:42.350
So, you get a sense of
what it looked like.

00:11:42.350 --> 00:11:44.410
And notice all the folds.

00:11:44.410 --> 00:11:49.810
Right. So, how do we retrace
the story of this scroll?

00:11:49.810 --> 00:11:54.620
Now, here you see it today
after it's been stabilized,

00:11:54.620 --> 00:11:57.860
not yet fully conserved,
but at least stabilized.

00:11:57.860 --> 00:12:00.500
And I want to draw
attention to Yasmeen Khan,

00:12:00.500 --> 00:12:02.270
who is sitting here
in the front row.

00:12:02.270 --> 00:12:05.320
Conservator here at the library,
who will be doing further work

00:12:05.320 --> 00:12:07.630
on the conservation
of this scroll

00:12:07.630 --> 00:12:10.990
in the weeks and months ahead.

00:12:10.990 --> 00:12:14.370
And here you have
the before and after.

00:12:14.370 --> 00:12:16.300
Now, I wrote before
and after conservation

00:12:16.300 --> 00:12:17.950
because I thought this
was already conserved,

00:12:17.950 --> 00:12:20.400
since it looked so good to
my eye in the photograph.

00:12:20.400 --> 00:12:22.120
But there Yasmeen
tells me no, it hasn't,

00:12:22.120 --> 00:12:23.570
actually, been conserved, yet.

00:12:23.570 --> 00:12:25.150
This is the stabilization.

00:12:25.150 --> 00:12:28.330
And at least, to get it onto
display, since it was on display

00:12:28.330 --> 00:12:34.050
in the Great Hall, here at the
library back in March and April.

00:12:34.050 --> 00:12:35.940
So, it looks like
to me, to my eye,

00:12:35.940 --> 00:12:38.070
that this has already been
put on the ironing board,

00:12:38.070 --> 00:12:41.290
don't try this at
home, and smoothed out.

00:12:41.290 --> 00:12:43.830
But apparently, there is still
much more work to be done.

00:12:43.830 --> 00:12:45.760
So, what are all
the folds about?

00:12:45.760 --> 00:12:48.290
Right. I mean, would,
we have no knowledge.

00:12:48.290 --> 00:12:51.770
We don't know how it
got from Russia in 1863,

00:12:51.770 --> 00:12:55.170
where it was, to London in 2001.

00:12:55.170 --> 00:12:57.150
But, I'll come back
and give you, at least,

00:12:57.150 --> 00:12:59.770
some speculation about that.

00:12:59.770 --> 00:13:01.070
Here's the note.

00:13:01.070 --> 00:13:02.370
You can see it much better now.

00:13:02.370 --> 00:13:06.590
Mainly in Russian,
but, also, some Hebrew

00:13:06.590 --> 00:13:12.560
and giving us the details,
which I described a moment ago.

00:13:13.870 --> 00:13:16.210
On the back of the, of
the back of the scroll.

00:13:16.210 --> 00:13:17.990
It's on the back of
the scroll, correct.

00:13:17.990 --> 00:13:19.290
Yeah, okay.

00:13:19.290 --> 00:13:21.670
Now, let me introduce you
to one of the great figures

00:13:21.670 --> 00:13:25.010
of Jewish history,
Abraham Firkovich.

00:13:25.010 --> 00:13:28.060
He was a hakham, a
wise man, literally.

00:13:28.060 --> 00:13:29.970
Meaning a leader of
the Karaite community.

00:13:29.970 --> 00:13:31.690
And those are the
years of his life.

00:13:31.690 --> 00:13:35.300
You can see that he lived
to be almost 100 years, no,

00:13:35.300 --> 00:13:37.360
to be almost 90 years old.

00:13:37.360 --> 00:13:41.660
And he is famous because
throughout the 19th century,

00:13:41.660 --> 00:13:44.850
he left Russia where he
was from, Karaite community

00:13:44.850 --> 00:13:46.160
that I just described.

00:13:46.160 --> 00:13:48.030
And he traveled throughout
the near East,

00:13:48.030 --> 00:13:52.480
and he brought back
manuscripts by huge numbers.

00:13:52.480 --> 00:13:56.340
Treasures of things that
had never been seen before

00:13:56.340 --> 00:13:58.020
by European scholars,

00:13:58.020 --> 00:14:01.520
as he traveled throughout
the Middle East in the land

00:14:01.520 --> 00:14:03.840
of Israel and in
Syria and in Egypt.

00:14:03.840 --> 00:14:06.940
And wherever he went in what
was then the Ottoman Empire.

00:14:06.940 --> 00:14:09.120
And he brought back
these great treasures.

00:14:09.120 --> 00:14:12.620
The most famous treasure he
brought back is the so-called

00:14:12.620 --> 00:14:15.880
Leningrad Codex, the
oldest complete copy

00:14:15.880 --> 00:14:18.200
of the Bible that we possess.

00:14:18.200 --> 00:14:21.950
With a colophon, a inscription
that, giving us information

00:14:21.950 --> 00:14:23.820
about the scribe and the year.

00:14:23.820 --> 00:14:29.240
Written in the year 1009 CE in
Tiberias in the land of Israel.

00:14:29.240 --> 00:14:30.730
And he brought that
back to Russia

00:14:30.730 --> 00:14:33.100
and it is now in St. Petersburg.

00:14:33.100 --> 00:14:36.140
When it was published
during the 1920s, the city,

00:14:36.140 --> 00:14:37.780
of course, was called Leningrad.

00:14:37.780 --> 00:14:40.470
So, people call it
the Leningrad Codex.

00:14:40.470 --> 00:14:43.470
I think we should start
calling it St. Petersburg Codex

00:14:43.470 --> 00:14:46.840
because the city has
reverted to that name.

00:14:46.840 --> 00:14:48.950
And of course, I do think
there's some irony in the fact

00:14:48.950 --> 00:14:51.410
that years from now, centuries
from now, or millennium

00:14:51.410 --> 00:14:53.330
from now, everybody
will have forgotten

00:14:53.330 --> 00:14:55.050
who Vladimir Lenin was.

00:14:55.050 --> 00:14:56.910
And his name will live
on only in the name

00:14:56.910 --> 00:14:58.210
of the Leningrad Codex.

00:14:58.210 --> 00:14:59.510
How's that for an irony?

00:14:59.510 --> 00:15:01.440
Of course, my students have
already forgotten who Lenin was.

00:15:01.440 --> 00:15:02.850
They think maybe was
one of the Beatles,

00:15:02.850 --> 00:15:05.400
but they don't even know
anything about that.

00:15:05.400 --> 00:15:08.610
Okay. So, Firkovich brings
the Leningrad Codex back

00:15:08.610 --> 00:15:10.850
and it is deposited
in the Imperial,

00:15:10.850 --> 00:15:13.220
what was then the Imperial
Library in St. Petersburg,

00:15:13.220 --> 00:15:15.280
where resides to
the present day.

00:15:15.280 --> 00:15:18.520
And presumably, he is the one
who must have brought the scroll

00:15:18.520 --> 00:15:22.110
that we have here at the Library
of Congress, scroll sheet back.

00:15:22.110 --> 00:15:23.750
We don't know that for sure,

00:15:23.750 --> 00:15:26.780
but his fingerprints,
quotation mark.

00:15:26.780 --> 00:15:30.060
Right. His fingerprints are all
over such a document that came

00:15:30.060 --> 00:15:34.970
from the Middle East
to Russia by a Karaite,

00:15:34.970 --> 00:15:36.270
into the Karaite community.

00:15:36.270 --> 00:15:39.550
And then, given to the royal
family, as I indicated.

00:15:39.550 --> 00:15:45.150
And then, presumably, somebody
got it out of the Russia,

00:15:45.150 --> 00:15:47.230
folded it up, smuggled it out.

00:15:47.230 --> 00:15:51.160
We don't know, and just
winds up, hence, the fold.

00:15:51.160 --> 00:15:52.960
And it just winds up
in London and it's

00:15:52.960 --> 00:15:56.030
on the auction market
in the year 2001.

00:15:56.030 --> 00:15:59.460
That's as much as we can say
about this, about the history

00:15:59.460 --> 00:16:02.650
of this, of this document.

00:16:02.650 --> 00:16:04.360
Now, as I mentioned before.

00:16:04.360 --> 00:16:06.280
Oh, and it was on
display, as I said,

