that are torn, that we can read.

00:16:51.060 --> 00:16:52.700
Or maybe they are complete

00:16:52.700 --> 00:16:55.060
but we can't read them,
they are so black.

00:16:55.060 --> 00:16:57.350
So, this gains the title

00:16:57.350 --> 00:17:00.130
of the oldest complete
Torah scroll sheet legible

00:17:00.130 --> 00:17:01.430
by the naked eye.

00:17:01.430 --> 00:17:03.980
Now, you can't see it on these
images, but on the far left

00:17:03.980 --> 00:17:07.580
and on the far right are
the remains of thread.

00:17:07.580 --> 00:17:11.740
So, remember that a Torah scroll
sheet, this is five columns,

00:17:11.740 --> 00:17:15.870
is written on a single
sheet of parchment.

00:17:15.870 --> 00:17:20.180
And then, they are sewn together
to create the large scroll

00:17:20.180 --> 00:17:22.270
with a large rolled text.

00:17:22.270 --> 00:17:26.130
So, this would have been
a single sheet connected

00:17:26.130 --> 00:17:29.620
to Genesis and the beginning
of Exodus on the one end.

00:17:29.620 --> 00:17:31.780
The rest of Exodus and
all of Leviticus, Numbers,

00:17:31.780 --> 00:17:35.360
and Deuteronomy, the five books
of the Torah on the other end.

00:17:35.360 --> 00:17:36.660
What happened to the rest?

00:17:36.660 --> 00:17:39.070
Why was the single
sheet preserved?

00:17:39.070 --> 00:17:41.600
Right. These are the
things we simply don't know.

