00:22:31.910 --> 00:22:36.370
I just wanted to point
out a few features

00:22:36.370 --> 00:22:38.390
of this scroll beyond
the poetry.

00:22:38.390 --> 00:22:45.650
Those of you who know Torah
scrolls, this predates some

00:22:45.650 --> 00:22:47.210
of the features of
the Torah scroll

00:22:47.210 --> 00:22:48.510
that you would be familiar with.

00:22:48.510 --> 00:22:52.020
First of all, there is
no left justification.

00:22:52.020 --> 00:22:54.380
Let's remember that Hebrew is
written from right to left.

00:22:54.380 --> 00:22:57.460
So, the columns begin
right justified.

00:22:57.460 --> 00:23:00.320
But there is no attempt to
do any left justification.

00:23:00.320 --> 00:23:01.700
Some lines are slightly shorter.

00:23:01.700 --> 00:23:03.200
Some lines are slightly longer.

00:23:03.200 --> 00:23:04.860
Can everybody see that, right?

00:23:04.860 --> 00:23:08.170
Today in the Middle Ages, the,
the tradition of doing right

00:23:08.170 --> 00:23:10.730
and left justification
developed.

00:23:10.730 --> 00:23:12.780
And so, this predates that.

00:23:12.780 --> 00:23:16.290
How did scribes the Middle Ages
do right and left justification?

00:23:16.290 --> 00:23:17.590
What if the long, what

00:23:17.590 --> 00:23:19.670
if the word was just
too long or too short?

00:23:19.670 --> 00:23:20.970
What they do?

00:23:20.970 --> 00:23:23.420
Right. They created what
we call dilated letters.

00:23:23.420 --> 00:23:26.970
They would take certain Hebrew
letters like the final Mem

00:23:26.970 --> 00:23:28.850
and stretch it out a little bit.

00:23:28.850 --> 00:23:30.880
Right. So, they would make,
they would get that right

00:23:30.880 --> 00:23:32.650
and left justification.

00:23:32.650 --> 00:23:35.790
You don't see that here.

00:23:35.790 --> 00:23:38.550
Seven letters of
the Hebrew alphabet

00:23:38.550 --> 00:23:41.850
in Torah scrolls have
little crowns on them.

00:23:41.850 --> 00:23:45.220
Little tittles on tops of
the letters, which we call

00:23:45.220 --> 00:23:48.190
in Hebrew, ''Tagin'',
meaning crowns.

00:23:48.190 --> 00:23:50.440
And these, this scroll
has none of that.

00:23:50.440 --> 00:23:53.350
Right. This doesn't, this
doesn't, this is not part

00:23:53.350 --> 00:23:56.190
of this tradition, yet.

00:23:56.190 --> 00:23:59.570
The last and the third feature,
which you do, which you see

00:23:59.570 --> 00:24:03.400
on medieval and contemporary
scrolls but you don't see here.

00:24:03.400 --> 00:24:08.680
There is a tradition to begin
each column with the letter Vav.

00:24:08.680 --> 00:24:11.910
The commonest letter in the
Hebrew alphabet is the word Vav,

00:24:11.910 --> 00:24:14.590
the letter Vav, which
means the word and.

00:24:14.590 --> 00:24:17.120
And it is so ubiquitous that
you could actually space

00:24:17.120 --> 00:24:20.100
out a Torah scroll and have
every single column begin

00:24:20.100 --> 00:24:21.400
with that letter Vav.

00:24:21.400 --> 00:24:23.090
What is known in the Hebrew
tradition is [foreign language],

00:24:23.090 --> 00:24:25.950
the Vavs of the columns.

00:24:25.950 --> 00:24:27.950
That is not present
here, either.

00:24:27.950 --> 00:24:31.400
So, no left justification,
no tagin, the little tittles,

00:24:31.400 --> 00:24:34.650
and no attempt to lay out the
text so that the letter Vav is

00:24:34.650 --> 00:24:36.160
at the beginning of each column.

00:24:36.160 --> 00:24:38.160
That is not to be
found here, at all.

00:24:38.160 --> 00:24:40.570
And of course, that
helps us understand

00:24:40.570 --> 00:24:44.010
that this is a very
ancient scroll,

00:24:44.010 --> 00:24:48.430
unlike all other,
all other scrolls.

00:24:48.430 --> 00:24:51.220
Also, and it's almost
impossible to see on this image,

00:24:51.220 --> 00:24:53.410
there are occasional
corrections.

00:24:53.410 --> 00:24:56.330
Now, according to Jewish law
and, certainly, as practiced

00:24:56.330 --> 00:24:59.860
by later scribes from, let's
say, the 13th century onward,

00:24:59.860 --> 00:25:01.430
if you make a mistake you have

00:25:01.430 --> 00:25:04.870
to scrape it off
or just restart.

00:25:04.870 --> 00:25:06.790
Or just, you know, can't use it

00:25:06.790 --> 00:25:09.160
for liturgical purposes
in the synagogue.

00:25:09.160 --> 00:25:13.000
This apparently either
ignores that or it's too early

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:17.030
to be participating in that
legal tradition or custom.

00:25:17.030 --> 00:25:21.300
And therefore, you do see
occasional corrections here.

00:25:21.300 --> 00:25:24.550
Some of them by, one of them
in particular, adds a word.

00:25:24.550 --> 00:25:28.410
I don't think you can
see it, but right up here

00:25:28.410 --> 00:25:32.500
between the lines, I mean,
I can't see it myself,

00:25:32.500 --> 00:25:33.800
either, at the moment.

00:25:33.800 --> 00:25:38.690
There is a, the Hebrew word
Et, which doesn't have, really,

00:25:38.690 --> 00:25:42.020
any meaning, but
note, it informs you

00:25:42.020 --> 00:25:44.540
that the direct object
is to follow,

00:25:44.540 --> 00:25:46.360
is inserted between
the two lines.

00:25:46.360 --> 00:25:48.320
Because the scribe had
left it out and went back

00:25:48.320 --> 00:25:49.700
and made that correction.

00:25:49.700 --> 00:25:51.400
And there's occasional
other corrections.

00:25:51.400 --> 00:25:55.700
One in particular, down here
and be, towards the bottom

00:25:55.700 --> 00:26:00.100
of the third column, where they
change the paragraphing system.

00:26:00.100 --> 00:26:02.720
You can see white spaces which
are indicating paragraphs.

00:26:02.720 --> 00:26:04.380
So, that was changed, as well.

00:26:04.380 --> 00:26:07.200
I do, I should point out that
the only place you see the left

00:26:07.200 --> 00:26:10.140
justification is in
the five prose lines

00:26:10.140 --> 00:26:12.190
in the upper left
before the song,

00:26:12.190 --> 00:26:15.310
and the five immediate
lines below the song.

00:26:15.310 --> 00:26:17.530
Right. Before the, above
and below the poem.

00:26:17.530 --> 00:26:22.050
There, you can actually see the
left justification, as well.

00:26:22.050 --> 00:26:23.880
Okay. Now, how do we know

00:26:23.880 --> 00:26:27.630
that this is really the oldest
complete Torah scroll sheet

00:26:27.630 --> 00:26:29.560
legible to the naked eye?

00:26:29.560 --> 00:26:30.860
Let's take a tour of that

00:26:30.860 --> 00:26:33.380
in the second half
of this presentation.

00:26:33.380 --> 00:26:37.160
So, the Ein Gedi Synagogue on
the shore of the Dead Sea dates

00:26:37.160 --> 00:26:39.800
to the fifth to the
seventh century.

00:26:39.800 --> 00:26:43.060
It was excavated in the 1970s.

00:26:43.060 --> 00:26:45.090
Here is a photo of the
way it looks, today.

00:26:45.090 --> 00:26:46.390
It's outdoors.

00:26:46.390 --> 00:26:47.690
You just see the foundation.

00:26:47.690 --> 00:26:49.070
How many of you have
been to Ein Gedi?

00:26:49.070 --> 00:26:52.340
Anybody? Worth a stop at
this beautiful synagogue

00:26:52.340 --> 00:26:53.640
with a mosaic floor.

00:26:53.640 --> 00:26:56.270
There's a tent over
it now, to protect it.

00:26:56.270 --> 00:27:02.840
And this is the area, this is
the area of the Torah scroll arc

00:27:02.840 --> 00:27:05.850
where the, would have been
a wooden box of some sort

00:27:05.850 --> 00:27:07.400
where the Torah scrolls
would have been kept.

00:27:07.400 --> 00:27:10.310
The Torah scroll
niche, the Torah niche.

00:27:10.310 --> 00:27:14.350
And in the excavations in
1970 this was found there.

00:27:14.350 --> 00:27:16.330
A burnt scroll.

00:27:16.330 --> 00:27:19.160
And it is charred,
it is impossible,

00:27:19.160 --> 00:27:20.780
must been an accidental fire.

00:27:20.780 --> 00:27:22.830
It is impossible to open up.

00:27:22.830 --> 00:27:25.610
The archaeologists just kept it.

00:27:25.610 --> 00:27:26.910
Right. They just kept it

00:27:26.910 --> 00:27:31.360
for 45 years thinking one
day technology will catch up.

00:27:31.360 --> 00:27:35.540
And it did, because we
now can do CT scanning,

00:27:35.540 --> 00:27:38.470
which you probably think was
invented for medical purposes

00:27:38.470 --> 00:27:40.880
but was really invented
to read old Torah scrolls.

00:27:40.880 --> 00:27:46.600
And here it is with the
Bruker Skyscan model 1176.

00:27:46.600 --> 00:27:48.900
Right. We have the 1076 at home.

00:27:48.900 --> 00:27:51.300
That's why we couldn't do
it ourselves, but we figured

00:27:51.300 --> 00:27:52.890
out how to do it with somebody.

00:27:52.890 --> 00:27:54.530
And they did the scroll.

00:27:54.530 --> 00:27:59.700
And here is, of course, it would
be black ink on white parchment,

00:27:59.700 --> 00:28:02.760
but you all know because
x-rays know these other kinds

00:28:02.760 --> 00:28:04.240
of MRIs and CT scans.

00:28:04.240 --> 00:28:05.970
It's always inverted imaging.

00:28:05.970 --> 00:28:08.130
And so, here is the
white letters.

00:28:08.130 --> 00:28:10.950
And turns out to be the
beginning of the book Leviticus.

00:28:10.950 --> 00:28:13.050
This was done in 2015.

00:28:13.050 --> 00:28:16.570
Next year, the scientists
went deeper into the scroll

00:28:16.570 --> 00:28:20.430
and this is still not been,
this is digitally unrolled.

00:28:20.430 --> 00:28:21.730
Do you realize what we're
talking about, here?

00:28:21.730 --> 00:28:24.080
Right. Digitally unwrapped,
digitally unrolled.

00:28:24.080 --> 00:28:27.050
And here is now the
complete scan

00:28:27.050 --> 00:28:30.790
of the scroll beginning
Exodus chapters one and two.

00:28:30.790 --> 00:28:34.740
You'll notice that there
is a blank sheet right

00:28:34.740 --> 00:28:36.850
in front of it, here.

00:28:36.850 --> 00:28:41.590
Okay. That tells us that this
scroll was not a complete scroll

00:28:41.590 --> 00:28:43.950
of Torah, but only the
book of Leviticus, right.

00:28:43.950 --> 00:28:45.250
Because, otherwise,
you'd see the end

00:28:45.250 --> 00:28:47.240
of Exodus before the
beginning of Leviticus.

00:28:47.240 --> 00:28:49.920
That it was just
Leviticus or, maybe,

00:28:49.920 --> 00:28:51.730
the second half of the Torah.

00:28:51.730 --> 00:28:54.060
Maybe, they used Genesis
and Exodus in one scroll,

00:28:54.060 --> 00:28:56.320
and then Leviticus, Numbers,
Deuteronomy in another.

00:28:56.320 --> 00:28:58.400
But this tells us this is
the beginning of the scroll

00:28:58.400 --> 00:29:00.830
and it starts with Leviticus.

00:29:00.830 --> 00:29:04.280
By the way, what do we call that
blank sheet at the beginning?

00:29:04.280 --> 00:29:06.150
A protocol.

00:29:06.150 --> 00:29:08.350
Protocol in Greek means
''that which was glued

00:29:08.350 --> 00:29:10.090
to the beginning of a scroll''.

00:29:10.090 --> 00:29:14.590
And in the Greek manuscripts or,
even in other later manuscripts,

00:29:14.590 --> 00:29:16.860
they would give you notations
as to what's in the scroll.

00:29:16.860 --> 00:29:18.510
So, you would just
have to open up.

00:29:18.510 --> 00:29:20.150
That was the protocol.

00:29:20.150 --> 00:29:22.970
Okay. The Jews didn't do that.

00:29:22.970 --> 00:29:25.690
They just put a blank sheet
there and didn't write on it

00:29:25.690 --> 00:29:28.330
because you just opened up
and saw it was Leviticus.

00:29:28.330 --> 00:29:31.240
And yes, there's a Lincoln penny
there because the scientists

00:29:31.240 --> 00:29:33.390
who did the work were at
the University of Kentucky.

00:29:33.390 --> 00:29:36.150
And so, this is there homage to
their most famous native son.

00:29:36.150 --> 00:29:42.270
At the Weitzman Institute
in Israel, it was subjected

00:29:42.270 --> 00:29:44.580
with a small piece
to a carbon-14 test

00:29:44.580 --> 00:29:47.020
and dated to around 300 CE.

00:29:47.020 --> 00:29:50.750
And since the synagogue is from
the sixth or seventh centuries,

00:29:50.750 --> 00:29:52.530
this informs us that
a scroll was in use

00:29:52.530 --> 00:29:53.830
for several centuries.

00:29:53.830 --> 00:29:56.580
Three-four centuries
inside the synagogue

00:29:56.580 --> 00:29:59.110
for liturgical purposes.

00:29:59.110 --> 00:30:01.090
And here it is, digitally
unwrapped now,

00:30:01.090 --> 00:30:02.390
with the black on white.

00:30:02.390 --> 00:30:04.890
Why we can play with the images.

00:30:04.890 --> 00:30:07.160
Thank you, scholars
and scientists,

00:30:07.160 --> 00:30:09.300
who help us out with
all of this work.

00:30:09.300 --> 00:30:13.490
This one is, actually,
in the US.

00:30:13.490 --> 00:30:16.350
This is known as
Ashkar-Gilson number two.

00:30:16.350 --> 00:30:19.510
It's in the David M.
Rubenstein Rare Book

00:30:19.510 --> 00:30:21.570
and Manuscript Library
at Duke University.

00:30:21.570 --> 00:30:24.220
And I mentioned his name because
he has been a great benefactor

00:30:24.220 --> 00:30:26.540
of book culture and is
a member of the Library

00:30:26.540 --> 00:30:29.370
of Congress Board,
if I'm not mistaken.

00:30:29.370 --> 00:30:34.400
So, he is a major player
in preserving books

00:30:34.400 --> 00:30:38.340
and manuscripts from
centuries ago.

00:30:38.340 --> 00:30:40.850
This is already digitally
enhanced.

00:30:40.850 --> 00:30:42.840
You can almost read
nothing of this.

00:30:42.840 --> 00:30:45.760
It so happens to,
also, be Exodus 15.

00:30:45.760 --> 00:30:49.750
And you can see the scroll,
the layout of the poem

00:30:49.750 --> 00:30:51.550
that we just read
and that we just saw

00:30:51.550 --> 00:30:54.010
on our scroll sheet,
you can see it here.

00:30:54.010 --> 00:30:56.240
But A, it's not complete, and B,

00:30:56.240 --> 00:30:58.440
it's almost impossible
to read anything.

00:30:58.440 --> 00:31:00.150
I've been to the Duke library.

00:31:00.150 --> 00:31:03.300
I've seen this with my own eyes
and, trust me, there's not much

00:31:03.300 --> 00:31:06.080
that one can actually
read by looking at it,

00:31:06.080 --> 00:31:09.780
unless you have some digital
enhancement as you see here.

00:31:09.780 --> 00:31:12.580
Here it is much more legible

00:31:12.580 --> 00:31:15.450
with some more photo
enhancement.

00:31:15.450 --> 00:31:18.600
Dated to around 700 CE.

00:31:18.600 --> 00:31:22.470
And there's an up
close, really beautiful.

00:31:22.470 --> 00:31:25.270
There is this scroll,
which was in London.

00:31:25.270 --> 00:31:27.440
How I got to London,
we don't know.

00:31:27.440 --> 00:31:32.590
It was in London for up until
the 20th century, and maybe even

00:31:32.590 --> 00:31:35.000
into the 21st century,
at Jews' College,

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:37.930
a training ground
for rabbis in the UK.

00:31:37.930 --> 00:31:40.950
And it's a complete sheet,

00:31:40.950 --> 00:31:44.630
as you can see here,
of seven columns.

00:31:44.630 --> 00:31:48.720
And it includes a large chunk
of the book of Exodus leading

00:31:48.720 --> 00:31:52.630
up to the material that we
just saw on the previous one.

00:31:52.630 --> 00:31:55.630
Now, this, also, cannot be
read with the naked eye.

00:31:55.630 --> 00:32:01.620
And it's now, also, in the
private hands of a collector.

00:32:01.620 --> 00:32:04.010
It has recently been
determined that these, actually,

00:32:04.010 --> 00:32:05.850
come from the same sheet.

00:32:05.850 --> 00:32:09.910
In other words, the paleography
experts who worked on this,

00:32:09.910 --> 00:32:13.310
the handwriting experts,
which we call paleographers.

00:32:13.310 --> 00:32:16.760
Now, tell us that the
London scroll on the right,

00:32:16.760 --> 00:32:18.200
which is now in private hands,

00:32:18.200 --> 00:32:22.120
and the Ashkar-Gilson
scroll fragment at Duke,

00:32:22.120 --> 00:32:26.710
come from the same scroll with
a column in between missing.

00:32:26.710 --> 00:32:29.990
And this was recently
worked out by Edna Engel

00:32:29.990 --> 00:32:33.720
and Mordechay Mishor
in Jerusalem.

00:32:35.030 --> 00:32:39.500
Ashkar-Gilson collection
has another scroll fragment.

00:32:39.500 --> 00:32:42.620
Nobody can read anything
on this.

00:32:42.620 --> 00:32:44.660
But, welcome to photography.

00:32:44.660 --> 00:32:48.510
Via multispectral imaging
we can read everything, now.

00:32:48.510 --> 00:32:51.620
And for those you who can
read Hebrew, this is a version

00:32:51.620 --> 00:32:55.140
of the Ten Commandments in the
book of Deuteronomy chapter 5.

00:32:55.140 --> 00:32:59.830
Isn't it great to live
in the 21st century

00:32:59.830 --> 00:33:02.450
where we can do all this?

00:33:02.450 --> 00:33:04.840
Here are some scroll sheets
that are, also, very old

00:33:04.840 --> 00:33:06.690
and are legible to
the naked eye.

00:33:06.690 --> 00:33:09.250
They all come from
the Cairo Genizah,

00:33:09.250 --> 00:33:11.390
Cambridge University
Library collection.

00:33:11.390 --> 00:33:13.780
TS stands for Taylor-Schechter.

00:33:13.780 --> 00:33:17.910
This one is dated to around 800
CE by the paleography experts.

00:33:17.910 --> 00:33:20.450
It's from Genesis, but
again, not complete.

00:33:20.450 --> 00:33:24.640
How do we know it's a Torah
scroll and not something else?

00:33:24.640 --> 00:33:26.530
Because the back is blank.

00:33:26.530 --> 00:33:29.760
Right. Eventually, the Jews
will move from the Torah scroll

00:33:29.760 --> 00:33:32.820
to the Codex, which is the
forerunner of the modern book,

00:33:32.820 --> 00:33:35.480
where you will have
writing on both sides.

00:33:35.480 --> 00:33:36.780
But all the things I'm talking

00:33:36.780 --> 00:33:39.390
about here are scrolls
and scroll sheets.

00:33:39.390 --> 00:33:42.040
Jews will continue to
use the scroll format

00:33:42.040 --> 00:33:44.480
down to the present
day in the synagogue

00:33:44.480 --> 00:33:47.140
for liturgical purposes of
the reading of the Torah

00:33:47.140 --> 00:33:48.550
and the book of Esther.

00:33:48.550 --> 00:33:50.220
But we can take images.

00:33:50.220 --> 00:33:51.970
We have images of these things

00:33:51.970 --> 00:33:55.850
to show us both the
recto and the verso.

00:33:55.850 --> 00:34:01.770
Here is a close-up of
just one small passage

00:34:01.770 --> 00:34:04.480
from Genesis chapter 14.

00:34:04.480 --> 00:34:05.970
And I've given you
the Hebrew text

00:34:05.970 --> 00:34:09.080
in its later Masoretic
apparatus,

00:34:09.080 --> 00:34:12.560
so you can comparison there.

00:34:12.560 --> 00:34:14.760
This comes from the
same scroll, as well,

00:34:14.760 --> 00:34:16.290
as the paleographers
now tell us.

00:34:16.290 --> 00:34:19.250
Also, in Cambridge, but the
earlier parts of Genesis.

00:34:19.250 --> 00:34:23.070
A small fragment from
around a century later.

00:34:23.070 --> 00:34:24.570
There it is blank.

00:34:24.570 --> 00:34:30.350
From a century later, we
have another fragment.

00:34:30.350 --> 00:34:31.650
See the seam?

00:34:31.650 --> 00:34:33.350
So, you can see how these
would have been two sheets

00:34:33.350 --> 00:34:34.860
that were sewn together.

00:34:34.860 --> 00:34:37.170
These are all in
Cambridge, originally found

00:34:37.170 --> 00:34:41.480
in the Cairo synagogue, the
Cairo Genizah collection.

00:34:41.480 --> 00:34:44.640
Blank on the reverse.

00:34:44.640 --> 00:34:49.100
One of the best examples of
what can happen in the history

00:34:49.100 --> 00:34:51.050
of manuscripts is this.

00:34:51.050 --> 00:34:53.370
Does everybody see what this is?

00:34:55.810 --> 00:34:58.080
Well, you can't come to a
Library of Congress talk

00:34:58.080 --> 00:35:00.910
in this division and not
hear the word palimpsest.

00:35:00.910 --> 00:35:02.950
This is a palimpsest.

00:35:02.950 --> 00:35:07.260
Right. It is an old
Hebrew manuscript

00:35:07.260 --> 00:35:09.840
where the ink was scraped off,

00:35:09.840 --> 00:35:14.370
and then a later scribe
wrote Greek on top of it.

00:35:14.370 --> 00:35:17.550
That, we call palimpsest,
where things were scraped off.

00:35:17.550 --> 00:35:19.830
This is from the used
parchment market.

00:35:19.830 --> 00:35:24.190
And we have so many palimpsests
from the early Middle Ages

00:35:24.190 --> 00:35:26.220
because it was hard
to get parchment.

00:35:26.220 --> 00:35:28.350
It was a lot of work
to get parchment.

00:35:28.350 --> 00:35:30.920
And so, you would have
to constantly rework it

00:35:30.920 --> 00:35:33.060
and scrape it and if
you did need it anymore.

00:35:33.060 --> 00:35:36.460
We don't know how this Hebrew
text was no longer being used.

00:35:36.460 --> 00:35:40.430
But it's a Torah scroll
underneath that was, somehow,

00:35:40.430 --> 00:35:45.400
got into Christian hands and a
Greek writing scribe wrote this.

00:35:45.400 --> 00:35:50.250
This is in the Medici
Library in Florence.

00:35:50.250 --> 00:35:55.060
And actually, we now know
from further analysis

00:35:55.060 --> 00:35:58.810
that six different handwritings
are on the under text.

00:35:58.810 --> 00:36:01.350
And it dates from more or less
the same time as the new Library

00:36:01.350 --> 00:36:03.110
of Congress Torah scroll sheet.

00:36:03.110 --> 00:36:05.970
And here we are, again.

00:36:05.970 --> 00:36:10.830
And so, with that
little review we can say,

00:36:10.830 --> 00:36:13.280
as I said a moment
ago, that the Library

00:36:13.280 --> 00:36:15.920
of Congress Torah scroll
sheet is the oldest sheet

00:36:15.920 --> 00:36:18.510
in the world legible
to the naked eye.

00:36:18.510 --> 00:36:20.410
Right. Do we have
all the material?

00:36:20.410 --> 00:36:23.000
Yes. Can we read them?

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:25.690
Either, they are fragmentary,
so they're not complete.

00:36:25.690 --> 00:36:27.100
Or we can't read them

00:36:27.100 --> 00:36:29.730
and we only need photo
enhancement to read them.

00:36:29.730 --> 00:36:33.300
So, here you have it to repeat
the oldest Torah scroll sheet

00:36:33.300 --> 00:36:37.830
legible to the naked eye, dated
to around 1,000 years ago.

00:36:37.830 --> 00:36:39.340
To conclude, if you're
interested

00:36:39.340 --> 00:36:43.870
where our oldest Torah scrolls
complete are to be found.

00:36:43.870 --> 00:36:46.440
And I've shown you very
fragmentary material.

00:36:46.440 --> 00:36:49.750
The oldest complete Torah
scroll in the world is

00:36:49.750 --> 00:36:53.580
in the University Library
in Bologna, recently dated

00:36:53.580 --> 00:36:58.090
with carbon-14 testing
to the year 1190 CE.

00:36:58.090 --> 00:37:03.100
And if you go back, in
this case, about 800 years,

00:37:03.100 --> 00:37:06.430
the plus minus of carbon-14
dating is really only

00:37:06.430 --> 00:37:08.320
about a 50-year window.

00:37:08.320 --> 00:37:12.450
So, it dates from 1140 to
1240, or something like that.

00:37:12.450 --> 00:37:15.610
In the C-14 test, we
split the difference

00:37:15.610 --> 00:37:17.550
and we come out with 1190.

00:37:17.550 --> 00:37:19.750
And you can see the image
has been opened up again

00:37:19.750 --> 00:37:21.730
to the same text that
we've been looking at,

00:37:21.730 --> 00:37:24.140
the poem of Exodus 15.

00:37:24.140 --> 00:37:26.930
Next time in your
Bologna, go to the library

00:37:26.930 --> 00:37:29.440
and request to see
this treasure.

00:37:29.440 --> 00:37:32.150
That's the oldest complete
Torah scroll we have.

00:37:32.150 --> 00:37:36.470
What about the oldest complete
Torah scroll still in use?

00:37:36.470 --> 00:37:40.730
Not in a university library,
still in a synagogue?

00:37:40.730 --> 00:37:43.430
At the northern Italian
city of Biella,

00:37:43.430 --> 00:37:46.570
where there is a small Jewish
community not far from Milan,

00:37:46.570 --> 00:37:49.090
this Torah scroll
is still in use.

00:37:49.090 --> 00:37:50.530
It's in the synagogue.

00:37:50.530 --> 00:37:53.620
And it, also, was recently
dated by carbon-14.

00:37:53.620 --> 00:37:55.200
You need just a little fleck.

00:37:55.200 --> 00:37:58.110
So, they took a little
fleck of the parchment.

00:37:58.110 --> 00:37:59.800
In the old days you'd
need huge amount,

00:37:59.800 --> 00:38:02.240
but today you can just take
like a fingernail worth.

00:38:02.240 --> 00:38:04.210
And both of these tests
were conducted, by the way,

00:38:04.210 --> 00:38:07.780
at the University of Illinois,
which has the best C-14 lab

00:38:07.780 --> 00:38:10.950
in the U.S. And why they send it
to the U.S. instead of someplace

00:38:10.950 --> 00:38:12.250
in Europe, I don't know.

00:38:12.250 --> 00:38:13.650
But they were both done here.

00:38:13.650 --> 00:38:15.660
And this one is from 1250 CE.

00:38:15.660 --> 00:38:19.470
Again, a plus minus of a
bit in either direction.

00:38:19.470 --> 00:38:23.030
But it gives you a sense of
how old these manuscripts are,

00:38:23.030 --> 00:38:28.290
how old and how well preserved
the ink on the parchment can be.

00:38:28.290 --> 00:38:31.700
Because these were done with
the best quality materials.

